{
  "text": "where Ω ⊆ R n is a convex, compact set containing the global minimum as an interior point that is defined by lower and upper bounds. It was later extended to problems with general constraints in [CITATION_1] . As most of the stochastic multistart methods, it consists of a global phase, where random points are sampled from a probabilistic distribution, and a local phase, where selected points from the global phase are used as starting points for local searches done by some local optimization algorithm. MLSL aims at avoiding unnecessary and costly local searches that culminate in the same local minima. To achieve this goal, sample points are drawn from an uniform distribution in the global phase and then a local search procedure is applied to each of them except if there is another sample point or a previously detected local minimum within a critical distance with smaller objective function value. The method is fully described in Algorithm 2.1. L * = L * ∪ LocalSearch(x i ) 8: end if 9: end for 10: end for 11: return the best local minimum found in L * The critical distance r k is defined as r k def = π −1/2 Γ 1 + n 2 m(S) σ log kN kN",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "96964222"
